00:23:00,493 --> 00:23:06,679
Developing the game was a little easier in playtesting because as a game that is non-competitive that is single-player

526
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:13,425
It's kind of more okay for certain powers to be a bit overpowered in certain situations and all that I was wondering like

527
00:23:14,246 --> 00:23:18,929
How did you make a decision between certain abilities being overpowered in a cool way

528
00:23:19,229 --> 00:23:23,352
later in the game or which abilities would be considered degenerate and which things

529
00:23:23,372 --> 00:23:27,034
would need to be reeled back from being too strong since you didn't have to worry about

530
00:23:27,054 --> 00:23:29,456
a negative play experience for an opponent?

531
00:23:30,490 --> 00:23:35,354
Sure. So a big part of it is how common it is to get that overpowered thing.

532
00:23:35,674 --> 00:23:39,076
It's like if we just had a common card that was way too powerful

533
00:23:39,156 --> 00:23:42,098
and you just saw it in every run, that's clearly no good.

534
00:23:42,258 --> 00:23:44,260
So one, you need things to be rare or hard to get.

535
00:23:45,661 --> 00:23:47,842
And then the other thing is just seeing how people play with it.

536
00:23:47,982 --> 00:23:49,544
So in general...

537
00:23:51,759 --> 00:23:53,761
that's a bit harder to get straight from metrics.

538
00:23:53,781 --> 00:23:55,442
You would need that more from like feedback,

539
00:23:56,203 --> 00:23:58,164
like people posting things in a feedback bot

