00:24:59,544 --> 00:25:00,445
You have two questions.

566
00:25:00,725 --> 00:25:04,768
The first is, what were your thoughts around having

567
00:25:04,808 --> 00:25:06,830
you discard the rest of your cards

568
00:25:06,870 --> 00:25:10,092
that you didn't use per turn instead of allowing a player

569
00:25:10,112 --> 00:25:12,094
to keep it so they could plan a turn ahead?

570
00:25:12,114 --> 00:25:15,436
And then my second one was kind of, yeah,

571
00:25:15,456 --> 00:25:16,457
so I'll ask the first one.

572
00:25:16,517 --> 00:25:16,877
Sure.

573
00:25:17,057 --> 00:25:19,079
So the first question is, why do you

574
00:25:19,119 --> 00:25:20,580
discard your hand at the end of turn

575
00:25:20,740 --> 00:25:22,582
instead of in a game like Hearthstone or Magic

576
00:25:22,602 --> 00:25:23,302
where you keep your hand?

577
00:25:24,271 --> 00:25:29,314
So that's actually kind of a holdover from deck building games like Dominion or Ascension

578
00:25:29,334 --> 00:25:33,596
and board games like that, where in those games you would always discard your hand into

579
00:25:33,616 --> 00:25:37,979
the discard pile, and I just kind of kept that model when building Sleight of the Spire.

580
00:25:38,119 --> 00:25:41,541
In general, what it does is it allows you to actually cycle through your deck and see

581
00:25:41,581 --> 00:25:44,162
all your cards, which is a property you really want.

582
00:25:46,638 --> 00:25:49,799
So we actually have a relic in the game called Runic Pyramid

583
00:25:50,139 --> 00:25:52,820
that lets you keep your hand, and you can see how it totally

584
00:25:52,860 --> 00:25:54,221
alters the play style of the game.

585
00:25:54,801 --> 00:25:58,403
It's more about holding onto cards and thinking about how

586
00:25:58,423 --> 00:26:00,423
you use them instead of being able to fly

587
00:26:00,463 --> 00:26:01,264
through your deck a lot.

588
00:26:01,824 --> 00:26:02,024
Sure.

589
00:26:02,464 --> 00:26:05,665
And so if you looked at the metrics around or feedback

590
00:26:05,705 --> 00:26:09,167
around that, did players like the former or the latter more?

591
00:26:09,187 --> 00:26:10,607
So.

592
00:26:12,602 --> 00:26:15,984
We never actually tested the game using

593
00:26:17,524 --> 00:26:19,345
the Hearthstone model of hand-holding

594
00:26:19,505 --> 00:26:21,906
because it was more based around deck builders,

595
00:26:22,447 --> 00:26:25,748
like Dominion, which is kind of the originator

596
00:26:25,788 --> 00:26:27,389
of the deck-building genre in board games,

597
00:26:27,529 --> 00:26:29,210
and in that game, you discard your hand.

598
00:26:29,290 --> 00:26:31,591
So I thought that what they were doing made sense there,

599
00:26:31,731 --> 00:26:33,692
and even in our original design document,

600
00:26:33,732 --> 00:26:35,753
we had it, and we just kind of kept going with that.

601
00:26:36,100 --> 00:26:37,361
Cool, and the second question, sorry,

602
00:26:37,822 --> 00:26:39,884
was have you guys thought about co-op,

603
00:26:39,924 --> 00:26:41,706
and if so, if you were to do co-op,

604
00:26:41,826 --> 00:26:43,428
how would you guys think through that?

605
00:26:45,831 --> 00:26:48,794
We've thought about co-op, maybe in the future,

606
00:26:49,034 --> 00:26:51,157
but basically no comment for co-op.

607
00:26:54,115 --> 00:26:55,576
First of all, thank you for the great talk.

608
00:26:56,257 --> 00:26:59,679
And my question is, so Slate the Spy has a lot of really good enemies

609
00:26:59,719 --> 00:27:01,820
that challenge the different card archetypes.

610
00:27:02,700 --> 00:27:04,982
So how did you go about enemy design?

611
00:27:05,002 --> 00:27:08,363
Did that come after the card design or were they sort of in tandem

612
00:27:08,444 --> 00:27:09,744
or did you have the enemies first?

613
00:27:10,805 --> 00:27:13,726
Most of the design for everything was kind of done in tandem.

614
00:27:13,847 --> 00:27:14,607
Like we...

615
00:27:16,113 --> 00:27:19,655
We created an initial set of like 20 or 30 cards

616
00:27:19,715 --> 00:27:21,855
and then started designing some basic enemies

617
00:27:22,035 --> 00:27:23,816
just to like make sure everything was good.

618
00:27:24,076 --> 00:27:25,456
Like the original version of the game,

619
00:27:26,337 --> 00:27:28,397
it just had a little single character

620
00:27:28,437 --> 00:27:29,658
that bobbed up and down.

621
00:27:29,678 --> 00:27:32,599
You had a couple basic enemies that were like zombies

622
00:27:32,659 --> 00:27:35,439
and slimes and you know, just stereotypical things.

623
00:27:35,479 --> 00:27:36,600
And you had basic cards.

624
00:27:36,620 --> 00:27:38,680
And then from there, we just fleshed everything out,

625
00:27:39,201 --> 00:27:40,381
started developing the world

626
00:27:40,441 --> 00:27:42,121
and we kind of just built organically.

627
00:27:42,971 --> 00:27:46,833
Casey and I would often meet up and we would just have design sessions where we would just

628
00:27:46,953 --> 00:27:51,416
hash out hundreds and hundreds of ideas in like a huge brainstorming session and then

629
00:27:51,456 --> 00:27:51,936
go from there.

630
00:27:52,316 --> 00:27:56,859
So we didn't just say, okay, now it's cards, now it's enemies, because everything's so

631
00:27:56,899 --> 00:27:57,379
interlinked.

632
00:27:58,660 --> 00:28:06,124
And just a quick follow-up, how did you decide to, I guess, make very predictable enemy attack

633
00:28:06,164 --> 00:28:06,544
patterns?

634
00:28:06,764 --> 00:28:08,325
Like, was that a conscious decision?

635
00:28:10,008 --> 00:28:12,369
So, how did we come up with our predictable

636
00:28:12,449 --> 00:28:13,289
enemy attack patterns?

637
00:28:14,609 --> 00:28:17,110
The enemy intent system and all of the,

638
00:28:18,210 --> 00:28:21,452
everything about that was actually a huge design process

639
00:28:21,492 --> 00:28:23,232
that took a long time to develop.

640
00:28:24,012 --> 00:28:25,613
The initial design of the game,

641
00:28:25,633 --> 00:28:28,274
they were more like, kind of like a Final Fantasy enemies,

642
00:28:28,374 --> 00:28:29,874
where they just had like random move sets

643
00:28:29,934 --> 00:28:31,535
and they would randomly roll and move every turn.

644
00:28:31,995 --> 00:28:33,615
And we actually had a lot of problems with this.

645
00:28:33,796 --> 00:28:34,656
Players felt that...

646
00:28:35,567 --> 00:28:36,347
It was too random.

647
00:28:37,348 --> 00:28:38,988
There's already a lot of randomness in the game

648
00:28:39,008 --> 00:28:40,589
with all the card elements and everything.

649
00:28:40,749 --> 00:28:42,929
So that extra element of unpredictability

650
00:28:42,969 --> 00:28:43,629
just didn't work.

651
00:28:44,189 --> 00:28:45,330
And then also you didn't know,

652
00:28:45,530 --> 00:28:47,150
like how much block do I need on this turn?

653
00:28:47,170 --> 00:28:49,471
I have no idea how much this enemy is attacking for.

654
00:28:50,031 --> 00:28:52,212
I don't have a good sense of can I attack or not?

655
00:28:52,352 --> 00:28:54,752
So we actually spent a long time

656
00:28:54,992 --> 00:28:56,933
and we went through a bunch of different systems on that.

657
00:28:56,953 --> 00:28:58,973
I could do like a whole talk on that, yeah.

658
00:29:01,043 --> 00:29:03,744
My question is about the unstructured feedback you're collecting.

659
00:29:03,804 --> 00:29:07,505
So, it's great to see that you had those channels to collect that kind of feedback,

660
00:29:07,565 --> 00:29:10,246
but how did you go about filtering through all that

661
00:29:10,286 --> 00:29:12,966
and actually being able to leverage it as a two-person team?

662
00:29:13,427 --> 00:29:15,627
Sure. So, one is you don't sleep.

663
00:29:17,748 --> 00:29:21,769
The other is you actually get better at it as you start to go through it.

664
00:29:24,170 --> 00:29:25,990
Honestly, we just had a manual process for it.

665
00:29:26,010 --> 00:29:28,251
We thought about trying to automate that feedback,

666
00:29:28,371 --> 00:29:29,871
but it's very difficult because...

667
00:29:31,038 --> 00:29:32,659
people can write the exact same bug

668
00:29:32,839 --> 00:29:34,700
into like 10 different ways, you know.

669
00:29:35,260 --> 00:29:38,902
So you will go through and we would look through it

670
00:29:39,062 --> 00:29:41,923
and we would try to organize things into different slots.

671
00:29:42,344 --> 00:29:44,745
Or we'd say, oh this is that bug I'm recognizing over here.

672
00:29:45,605 --> 00:29:47,346
And we would chat with each other while we're doing it.

673
00:29:48,466 --> 00:29:50,567
And honestly, we just did it manually

674
00:29:50,747 --> 00:29:54,049
and kind of developed that skill over time.

675
00:29:54,489 --> 00:29:56,890
But there was no easy solution.

676
00:29:57,150 --> 00:29:57,891
Cool, thank you.

677
00:29:58,828 --> 00:30:02,751
Hi. Regarding daily challenges, are you creating those procedurally or are you hand-making them?

678
00:30:02,871 --> 00:30:04,633
And how much balance are you putting on them?

679
00:30:04,653 --> 00:30:09,756
Sure. So regarding daily challenges, are we making them procedurally or hand-making them?

680
00:30:09,856 --> 00:30:11,538
I am absolutely not hand-making them.

681
00:30:12,258 --> 00:30:15,580
Those are procedurally generated based on basically the date.

682
00:30:16,021 --> 00:30:19,063
So we hit a time server, get a time stamp for the day,

683
00:30:19,363 --> 00:30:22,445
and then use that as the seed to procedurally generate everything.

684
00:30:23,010 --> 00:30:25,571
And it's funny because a lot of people think that,

685
00:30:25,591 --> 00:30:27,372
you know, I'm sitting there every day,

686
00:30:27,412 --> 00:30:28,812
like on Christmas day, I'm like,

687
00:30:28,912 --> 00:30:31,673
all right, this is the, and I never did that.

688
00:30:31,753 --> 00:30:34,214
But because of some of the patterns that emerge,

689
00:30:34,434 --> 00:30:36,634
players get that impression, which is great,

690
00:30:36,795 --> 00:30:39,035
because, you know, some people really like that,

691
00:30:39,075 --> 00:30:40,376
but I'm absolutely not doing that.

692
00:30:40,636 --> 00:30:42,416
And are you spending any time balancing it

693
00:30:42,456 --> 00:30:43,257
or are you just letting it go?

694
00:30:43,696 --> 00:30:44,436
No, we just let it go.

695
00:30:45,057 --> 00:30:46,017
And what we do is,

696
00:30:46,938 --> 00:30:49,059
it's one of the things that we can use our metrics on

697
00:30:49,099 --> 00:30:51,580
to look at retroactively and see,

698
00:30:51,761 --> 00:30:54,842
like, we ended up changing and getting rid of Brewmaster,

699
00:30:55,222 --> 00:30:59,985
which was a daily modifier that ended up being no fun.

700
00:31:00,205 --> 00:31:01,586
But that's the kind of thing where you just,

701
00:31:01,686 --> 00:31:03,767
you test it, you see how it's received.

702
00:31:04,188 --> 00:31:06,709
It wasn't received well, so we modified it.

703
00:31:06,729 --> 00:31:07,509
All right, thanks.

704
00:31:08,778 --> 00:31:10,599
So you're drinking from the feedback firehose,

705
00:31:11,400 --> 00:31:13,961
and the emotional load of that, how do you deal with it?

706
00:31:14,041 --> 00:31:15,722
Because I know, you know, sometimes people are toxic,

707
00:31:15,742 --> 00:31:18,203
sometimes they're not, but even if you've got the same piece

708
00:31:18,263 --> 00:31:21,284
of feedback 300 times about something you don't want

709
00:31:21,304 --> 00:31:22,905
to change, how did you guys manage that?

710
00:31:23,618 --> 00:31:26,621
So I just want to make sure I got that right.

711
00:31:26,681 --> 00:31:29,584
So how do we manage getting like 300 pieces of the same feedback?

712
00:31:29,604 --> 00:31:32,207
So specifically the emotional load of it,

713
00:31:32,307 --> 00:31:34,989
because if you're getting a lot of feedback,

714
00:31:35,530 --> 00:31:38,253
even when it's polite, it's a lot of feedback.

715
00:31:38,293 --> 00:31:41,196
And I know that can be challenging to handle emotionally.

716
00:31:42,633 --> 00:31:45,997
Okay, so how do you deal with the emotional aspect of getting that feedback?

717
00:31:47,459 --> 00:31:50,042
You just hit delete on that piece of feedback if it's trash.

718
00:31:50,803 --> 00:31:51,944
I mean, it's really that simple.

719
00:31:53,426 --> 00:31:55,889
You even get to the point where you're like, oh, it's this guy again.

720
00:31:56,149 --> 00:31:58,132
I recognize the avatar, delete.

721
00:31:59,761 --> 00:32:01,022
I mean, let's be realistic.

722
00:32:01,082 --> 00:32:04,704
So, not every piece of feedback is created equally,

723
00:32:04,864 --> 00:32:06,725
and so sometimes we'll have some people

724
00:32:06,765 --> 00:32:08,205
that we really recognize,

725
00:32:08,245 --> 00:32:11,327
like they'll give big, detailed pieces of feedback,

726
00:32:11,387 --> 00:32:12,488
and so I'll be like, oh, it's him.

727
00:32:12,668 --> 00:32:14,188
Okay, I'll make sure to pay attention to this.

728
00:32:14,769 --> 00:32:19,251
But you just kind of get mute to the constant nonsense.

729
00:32:19,571 --> 00:32:23,393
So it was just something, at first it was a little jarring,

730
00:32:23,813 --> 00:32:26,675
and by the 18,000th piece of feedback,

731
00:32:26,695 --> 00:32:27,295
you're like, whatever.

732
00:32:27,315 --> 00:32:28,896
Thank you, great talk.

733
00:32:30,611 --> 00:32:30,731
Hi.

